<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-tools" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Software Tools</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This appendix gives a brief introduction to the software packages required
      for working with R Markdown and <c>bookdown</c>, with an emphasis on how
      to install and maintain the core tools.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="r-and-r-packages">
    <title>R and R packages</title>

    <p>
      R can be downloaded from a CRAN mirror such as
      <url href="https://cran.rstudio.com" visual="cran.rstudio.com"/>. Since R
      has several releases each year, the chapter notes that you may want to
      upgrade it occasionally.
    </p>

    <p>
      To install <c>bookdown</c>, the Rmd source first gives the simplest
      package-installation command.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>install.packages("bookdown")</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      It then shows how to install optional dependencies as well, which can be
      convenient if you do not mind installing packages that may not be used in
      a given project.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>install.packages("bookdown", dependencies = TRUE)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      To test the development version from GitHub, the chapter recommends
      installing <c>devtools</c> first if necessary and then installing
      <c>bookdown</c> from the repository.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>if (!requireNamespace('devtools')) install.packages('devtools')
devtools::install_github('rstudio/bookdown')</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Since packages on CRAN and GitHub are updated regularly, the chapter also
      suggests updating your installed packages from time to time.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>update.packages(ask = FALSE)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Although it is not required, the chapter also recommends the RStudio IDE
      as a convenient environment for R-related work. The RStudio IDE can be
      downloaded from <url href="https://www.posit.co"
      visual="posit.co"/>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="pandoc">
    <title>Pandoc</title>

    <p>
      An R Markdown document (<c>*.Rmd</c>) is first compiled to Markdown
      (<c>*.md</c>) through the <c>knitr</c> package, and then Markdown is
      compiled to other output formats (such as LaTeX or HTML) through Pandoc.
      This process is automated by the <c>rmarkdown</c> package. You do not
      need to install <c>knitr</c> or <c>rmarkdown</c> separately, because they
      are the required packages of <c>bookdown</c> and will be automatically
      installed when you install <c>bookdown</c>. However, Pandoc is not an R
      package, so it will not be automatically installed when you install
      <c>bookdown</c>. You can follow the installation instructions on the
      Pandoc homepage (<url href="http://pandoc.org" visual="pandoc.org"/>) to
      install Pandoc, but if you use the RStudio IDE, you do not really need to
      install Pandoc separately, because RStudio includes a copy of Pandoc. The
      Pandoc version number can be obtained via:
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>rmarkdown::pandoc_version()</input>
      <output>[1] '1.19.2.1'</output>
    </program>

    <p>
      If you find this version too low and there are Pandoc features only in a
      later version, you can install the later version of Pandoc, and
      <c>rmarkdown</c> will call the newer version instead of its built-in
      version.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="latex">
    <title>LaTeX</title>

    <p>
      LaTeX is required only if you want to convert your book to PDF. You may
      see <url href="https://www.latex-project.org/get/"
      visual="latex-project.org/get/"/> for more information about LaTeX and
      its installation, but we strongly recommend that you install the
      lightweight and cross-platform LaTeX distribution named
      <url href="https://yihui.org/tinytex/" visual="TinyTeX"/> and based on
      TeX Live. TinyTeX can be easily installed through the R package
      <c>tinytex</c> (which should be automatically installed when you install
      <c>bookdown</c>):
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>tinytex::install_tinytex()</input>
    </program>

    <p>With TinyTeX, you should never see error messages like this:</p>

    <program language="latex-error">
      <input>! LaTeX Error: File `titling.sty' not found.

Type X to quit or &lt;RETURN&gt; to proceed,
or enter new name. (Default extension: sty)

Enter file name:
! Emergency stop.
&lt;read *&gt;

l.107 ^^M

pandoc: Error producing PDF
Error: pandoc document conversion failed with error 43
Execution halted</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The above error means you used a package that contains
      <c>titling.sty</c>, but it was not installed. LaTeX package names are
      often the same as the <c>*.sty</c> filenames, so in this case, you can
      try to install the <c>titling</c> package. If you use TinyTeX with R
      Markdown, missing LaTeX packages will be installed automatically, so you
      never need to worry about such problems.
    </p>

    <p>
      LaTeX distributions and packages are also updated from time to time, and
      you may consider updating them especially when you run into LaTeX
      problems. You can find out the version of your LaTeX distribution by:
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>res &lt;- base::system('pdflatex --version', intern = TRUE)
res &lt;- paste("## ", res)
res &lt;- paste0(res, collapse = "\n")</input>
      <output>## pdfTeX 3.141592653-2.6-1.40.24 (TeX Live 2022)
## kpathsea version 6.3.4
## Copyright 2022 Han The Thanh</output>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>system('pdflatex --version')</input>
      <output>## pdfTeX 3.141592653-2.6-1.40.24 (TeX Live 2022)
## kpathsea version 6.3.4
## Copyright 2022 Han The Thanh</output>
    </program>

    <p>
      For maintenance, the chapter recommends updating TinyTeX packages when you
      run into LaTeX problems and reinstalling TinyTeX entirely if an annual
      upgrade becomes necessary.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>tinytex::tlmgr_update()</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>tinytex::reinstall_tinytex()</input>
    </program>
  </section>
</chapter>
